				\begin{document}$$(\partial T)$$\end{document}(∂T). Dust affects Earth’s radiative balance directly through interactions with radiation, termed the direct radiative effect (DRE), and indirectly through interactions with clouds, biogeochemistry, and the cryosphere2,3. These indirect effects are poorly understood, with large and poorly quantified uncertainties2,3. We therefore restrict our discussion to the direct dust–climate feedback arising from changes in the dust direct radiative effect only, which is better understood and has a better quantified uncertainty1.

